{
  "text": "Taken together, the pathogenesis of T. foetus on the intestinal epithelial cells is both contact -dependent and contact -independent. In the former, cytopathic effect is mainly via apoptosis induced by cell-associated proteases, whereas extracellular proteases are the major players in contact -independent cytotoxicity. Extracellular proteases may also play a role in evading complement killing. Consequently proteases are a major player although other uncharacterized molecules may also contribute to pathogenesis of this intriguing trichomonad. Consistent with the notion, 483 and 445 bovine and feline isolates of T. foetus transcripts were determined to be proteases by a transcriptomical approach. Among these 389 and 346 were CP, respectively [CITATION_1] .",
